{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512719"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11943"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11943"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.16,0.03,0.05,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4539"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112957"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4539"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94989"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1715"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46473"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112957"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with swelling of her lips and tongue. She has a medical history of hypertension. Her medications include a new antihypertensive medication and daily low dose aspirin. On examination, mild lip and tongue swelling is noted. Her pulse rate is 85 /min, blood pressure 130/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16 /min, SpO2 is 98 % on room air and temperature 36.7 \u00b0C. She is observed over the next hour within the Emergency Department and her symptoms worsen with increased swelling of the lips and tongue and swelling of the face.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely to have caused this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin","Diltiazem","Furosemide","Metoprolol","Enalapril"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient described in the stem is suffering from angioedema. This is a rare, but potentially devastating adverse effect of angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors (ACEi), such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eenalapril\u003C/strong\u003E. Angioedema secondary to ACEi is usually limited to the face, tongue and lips\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eand is frequently asymmetric. In severe cases, there may be involvement of the uvula, pharyngeal or laryngeal structures and subsequent airway compromise. This complication requires immediate escalation for endotracheal intubation (ETT) or \u0027front of neck\u0027 airway in cases where ETT is not possible. Additionally, the causative medication should be immediately ceased, and notes should be made to never re-challenge ACEi in the future.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImportantly, risk factors for ACEi-induced angioedema include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPersonal history of ACEi-induced cough (approximately nine times increased risk)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfrican descent (approximately four times increased risk)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmoking\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdvanced age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFemale gender\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUse of concurrent NSAIDs and calcium channel blockers\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough similar in action, angiotensin receptor blockers (ARBs) cause angioedema far less frequently, with episodes thought not to be as severe as those caused by their ACEi counterparts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe major differential diagnosis in this presentation would be an anaphylactic reaction involving the upper airways. In situations such as this you would find the patient becoming increasingly short of breath and hypotensive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiltiazem \u003C/strong\u003Eis a non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker and is not linked with angioedema as a potential adverse drug reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide \u003C/strong\u003Eis a loop diuretic that has no links with angioedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol \u003C/strong\u003Eis a beta-adrenoreceptor antagonist and has no links with angioedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Angioedema of the lips, tongue and face is a rare but significant complication of angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors.","Management of ACEi-induced angioedema includes immediate cessation of ACEi, supportive care for mild cases and facilitating access to airway management where required."],"references":["Weisman DS, Arnouk N, Asghar MB, Qureshi MR, Kumar A, Desale S, Camire L, Pineda S. ACE inhibitor angioedema: characterization and treatment versus non-ACE angioedema in acute hospitalized patients. J Community Hosp Intern Med Perspect. 2020;10(1):16-18. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32128053/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94989"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11943"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}}